    "severity": "medium",
    "description": "The `_memberInfoCache` dictionary uses `Expression` as a key, which relies on reference equality. In Blazor, lambda expressions passed as component parameters are new objects on each render cycle, so the cache never matches across renders and grows without bound — a memory leak. The `_displayNameCache` (keyed by `MemberInfo`, which is stable and shared across instances) already provides the necessary caching for the expensive attribute-reflection work. The expression cache is both useless and harmful.",
    "fix_applied": true
  },
  {
    "file": "src/Components/Web/src/Forms/DisplayName.cs",
    "line": 46,
    "severity": "medium",
    "description": "The `if (For != _previousFieldAccessor)` guard uses reference equality on lambda expression objects. Blazor creates a new `Expression<Func<TValue>>` instance on every render, so this comparison is always true and the 'skip re-computation' optimization is never triggered. Storing `_previousFieldAccessor` is unnecessary state that provides no benefit. The inner check `if (newDisplayName != _displayName)` is the correct and sufficient render guard; the outer expression-reference check is a compliance violation (ineffective optimization that adds dead state) and should be removed.",
    "fix_applied": true
  }
]

